• Increases in both carbon dioxide (CO2) concentrations and air temperatures are expected to cause production increases in some crops grown in the Puget Sound region.
  • Increasing air temperatures could increase the number of grape varieties best suited to growing in Washington's temperate regions, including the Puget Sound region. The warmer climate projected west of the Cascades would make it easier to grow grapes in areas that are currently unsuitable due to low growing season temperatures.
  • Projections suggest that the Puget Sound lowlands may become newly suitable for viticulture by 2050 (2041-2060), under both a low and a high greenhouse gas scenario. Check this on map.

Interact with the map below to understand which grapes are/will be suitable for specific farmlands

New areas are becoming suitable for cultivating wine grapes. The maps above show projected changes in areas of climatic suitability for grapes for 2050 (2041-2060, relative to 1971-2000), under a low (RCP 4.5) and high (RCP 8.5) greenhouse gas scenario. Area suitable for viticulture is projected to increase from ~1.7 million acres to <+ 22 million acres under RCP 4.5 and to <+ 29 million acres under RCP 8.5 (increasing by a factor of 13 and 19, respectively). Results for both greenhouse gas scenarios indicate that the lowlands of Puget Sound will become newly suitable for grape production. Figure source: Hannah et al. 2013
